        "formula": "Given input X with shape (N, C_in, H_in, W_in) and weight W with shape (C_out, C_in, K_h, K_w), the output Y is computed as a 2D convolution with stride (S_h, S_w), dilation (D_h, D_w), and zero-padding (P_h, P_w). The output spatial dimensions are:\nH_out = floor((H_in + 2*P_h - D_h*(K_h - 1) - 1) / S_h + 1)\nW_out = floor((W_in + 2*P_w - D_w*(K_w - 1) - 1) / S_w + 1)\nFor n in [0, N-1], oc in [0, C_out-1], h in [0, H_out-1], w in [0, W_out-1]:\n  Y[n, oc, h, w] = sum_{ic=0}^{C_in-1} sum_{kh=0}^{K_h-1} sum_{kw=0}^{K_w-1} \n      X[n, ic, h*S_h + kh*D_h - P_h, w*S_w + kw*D_w - P_w] * W[oc, ic, kh, kw]\nwhere X[n, ic, ih, iw] is taken as 0 if ih < 0 or ih >= H_in or iw < 0 or iw >= W_in (zero padding).",
        "boundary_treatment": "The input X is implicitly zero-padded. Specifically, P_h rows of zeros are added above and below, and P_w columns of zeros are added to the left and right. Any convolution window accessing indices outside [0, H_in-1] × [0, W_in-1] receives zero values. This corresponds to the standard 'zeros' padding mode in PyTorch. There is no output padding or other boundary adjustments.",
